<Rate>3< /Rate>< text>
There are some major communications issues within this complex.  If you have an emergency on Friday evening and are told to come back Saturday, be prepared to wait forever and get very little accomplished because one department won't have access to your x-rays, etc. because that other department isn't open on weekends.  Oh, and forget about getting a cast on a weekend, too.  I only give this 3 stars because the staff is competent but hindered.  The facilities are clean, bright and calming and everyone we came in contact with was friendly.  We actually got to see an MD (Not an RN, NP, etc.), which is becoming increasingly difficult.  One huge plus is that we were referred and got approval almost instantly and were seen right away.< /text>

< Text>
I suffered a concussion when I fell off of my bicycle. I do not know recall my fall as I was unconscious when I hit my head, but when I woke up in an ambulance, I had lots of bruises and abrasion on my body. They decided to take me to Sharp Memorial Hospital. This was around 17:00 on January 22nd, 2018.
The review here is for the staff that took care of me at the ER. I am very thankful for the doctor (I do not remember him, but it was an older male) that examined me. And I am very grateful and thankful to the nurse (Jackie) that took care of me. She treated every of my wounds and patched me up. I just wanted to say thank you so much for taking care of me. Their customer service is marvelous. They go out of their way to care for you when you come in. Everyone here is nice and genuine. I am glad that my injury is not serious.
They are also nice to tell you what happened to you as in explaining the injury and answering all your questions. The nurse that assisted me with everything was kind and professional.
Anyways, it will be a little while before I recover from my fall, but I will rest up. Now as for the medical bill.....that will sting me which is part of life. I do know they are willing to work with me on that so it is a bit reassuring. But the service that you get here is outstanding. Thank you so much for treating me here.
Looks like it will be a little while before I will write another Yelp review as I am having a hard time enjoying food. Once I recover, (hopefully next month) I shall reward myself with good food and write more Yelp reviews.
NOTE: Although I give it a 5 stars, just keep in mind that most are genuinely nice. There are few that would have a bad day, but they will all help you if you are nice and polite. As a person that worked at a customer service job in the past, I can say that most people here will give a great customer service to you.</Text>

< Rating>
1</Rating>
<text>Recently I was in the ER and admitted to Sharp Memorial. This was my second time here at this hospital and I was greatly displeased from start to finish. I could not catch my breath and felt like I was drowning. The person who was working the front desk told my husband and I, very rudely might I add, that we "Had to wait and just stand right there, I'm busy." So here I am standing there barely holding on and couldn't even talk. Finally we are able to sit down and he began taking my vitals my another woman was taking my information. This man looks at me and says well your breathing is fine, it's 100%(which he says with a smirk). Yeah, my oxygen is at 100% because I am hyperventilating and trying to stay alive. I get back to a room and they start telling me I need to calm down. I understand that I need to calm down, but when you can catch your breath it's hard to be relaxed. How about trying to get my breathing under control first? They couldn't figure out what was going on, so they decided to admit me. The entire time I was admitted they tried doing the same treatments over and over. Even though these treatments did not work and often times made my heart rate go fast. Oh I forgot to mention, the week before I came here (after being sent from Urgent Care) for a high heart rate and breathing issues for which I was diagnosed with Bronchitis. They refused to give me antibiotics because the "the side affects just aren't worth it". They only gave me steroids, which obviously did not work. The two problems that made me ask for my own discharge was an unprofessional Nurse and Respiratory Therapist. The RT told me that everything that was going on (one was my heart rate jumping to 180 while resting) was all in my mind and that I was just having panic attacks. Really? I'm so glad that you can diagnosis me with an anxiety disorder when that's not even your profession. The next was when my Nurse came in and told me that there was no way I had asthma (which I have been diagnosed with for the past 12 years) because I don't wheeze, my lungs just tighten up. Hmmm.... that's funny considering there is some times that I wheeze and other times where I tighten up. After discussing this with the RT she said that wheezing is not necessarily a necessity for or the only indicator for Asthma. This whole time I was here they wanted to treat the symptoms, not the actual problem. I will now be following up with my Primary and having a referral to see a real specialist to figure out what's going on. The only reason why I am giving this hospital 1 star is because of the nurses that I had that were just phenomenal! Without those nurses I probably wouldn't be here today. So thank you to those ladies who kept me alive!< /text>< pics>
None< /pics>

<rate>1<//rate><Gmap_id>0x80d9555f40070df1:0x7c4c50bfdc73c9f5</Gmap_id>< Review>
Recently I was in the ER and admitted to Sharp Memorial. This was my second time here at this hospital and I was greatly displeased from start to finish. I could not catch my breath and felt like I was drowning. The person who was working the front desk told my husband and I, very rudely might I add, that we "Had to wait and just stand right there, I'm busy." So here I am standing there barely holding on and couldn't even talk. Finally we are able to sit down and he began taking my vitals my another woman was taking my information. This man looks at me and says well your breathing is fine, it's 100%(which he says with a smirk). Yeah, my oxygen is at 100% because I am hyperventilating and trying to stay alive. I get back to a room and they start telling me I need to calm down. I understand that I need to calm down, but when you can catch your breath it's hard to be relaxed. How about trying to get my breathing under control first? They couldn't figure out what was going on, so they decided to admit me. The entire time I was admitted they tried doing the same treatments over and over. Even though these treatments did not work and often times made my heart rate go fast. Oh I forgot to mention, the week before I came here (after being sent from Urgent Care) for a high heart rate and breathing issues for which I was diagnosed with Bronchitis. They refused to give me antibiotics because the "the side affects just aren't worth it". They only gave me steroids, which obviously did not work. The two problems that made me ask for my own discharge was an unprofessional Nurse and Respiratory Therapist. The RT told me that everything that was going on (one was my heart rate jumping to 180 while resting) was all in my mind and that I was just having panic attacks. Really? I'm so glad that you can diagnosis me with an anxiety disorder when that's not even your profession. The next was when my Nurse came in and told me that there was no way I had asthma (which I have been diagnosed with for the past 12 years) because I don't wheeze, my lungs just tighten up. Hmmm.... that's funny considering there is some times that I wheeze and other times where I tighten up. After discussing this with the RT she said that wheezing is not necessarily a necessity for or the only indicator for Asthma. This whole time I was here they wanted to treat the symptoms, not the actual problem. I will now be following up with my Primary and having a referral to see a real specialist to figure out what's going on. The only reason why I am giving this hospital 1 star is because of the nurses that I had that were just phenomenal! Without those nurses I probably wouldn't be here today. So thank you to those ladies who kept me alive!</Review>

< Review>
I really liked Dr. Brewster and all of the other people involved.  I had a polyp in my nose removed.  They never quoted me a price.  I simply relied on internet message boards and doctor websites for cost estimates, which seemed reasonable.   However I was shocked to get a bill for $42,000.  This was more than my friend's hip replacement surgery, and 3-4 times what other medical groups estimate on healthcare estimate websites.  I'm scheduled for other procedures in 2019 but will be cancelling due to the major bills they are now charging me for the next
year.

Here's what's also disturbing.  During his assessment, Dr. Brewster diagnosed me with another disease but didn't bother to tell me.  He buried this in his notes, which I only discovered months after my surgery.  How ethical is it not to disclose a disease to a patient?<//Review>

< Text>
Unfortunately I've been a patient at this hospital more often than I would have liked, however if you need to be in a hospital it would be very difficult to find a better one. Staff are extremely friendly, helpful knowledgeable and kind especially the nurses who work so hard but always with a smile and comforting words . The rooms are clean, comfortable and well equipped. Parking is easier than most hospitals. Most procedures are carried out on site. The ER gets overwhelmed sometimes with lengthy waits, but most ER's seem to suffer from the same problem. Really there's nothing to complain about with this facility.</Text>

< review>
In my entire life I have never been ripped off by a business as bad as what Sharp Memorial did to me.  I went to the emergency room to have a bicycle injury looked at, which had occurred about 7 days prior.  I talked to a doctor for no more than 10 minutes, who said I had a hematoma, and he ordered an x-ray, which I protested at first but since he's the doctor I agreed.  After the x-ray and 2 more hours of waiting, a Sharp Payment Person came to my bedside and told me I had to pay a "deposit" of $1500 of which I might get some of it refunded.  As soon as I paid, the doctor came and told me my x-ray showed no broken bones which I already predicted, and he told me to ice the bruise and sent me on my way. Big Surprise, there was no refund and the "deposit" turned into exactly what I owed them!  It was a trick, they lied to me.  THEN a week later I got another bill in the mail for the x-ray, THEN another week later I got a bill for "Emergency Services". Total cost for 10 minutes of talking to a doctor and x-ray: $1900. I don't have insurance because I can't afford it, and I guess the way the system works is people who don't have insurance get overcharged to the maximum. I later learned that if I had gone to one of those Urgent Care Clinics, the exact same service would have cost $170. I won't be going to Sharp Memorial again.
Edit: after receiving the response below from the Sharp "Patient Relations Team", I called the number and spoke to someone who told me that the bill I got is what I owe. I don't know what was the point of me calling except for wasting my time. But to summarize, if you don't have insurance then you are fair game to be ripped off with an absurd bill.  $1900 for 10 minutes with a doctor and a few x-rays!!!! Unbelievable.< /review>

<Time>1507335432046< /Time><Rate>5< /Rate><Text>Sharp Memorial Hospital is one of the best hospitals in San Diego County.The Rady Children's Hospital - world renowned for its cancer research - is located on the hospital grounds, as well as the Sharp Mary Birch Hospital for Women and Newborns; the Sharp Rehabilitation Center and the Mesa Vista Drug Treatment and Behavioural Center,are all subdivisions of this marvelous clinical complex.
They are located at the prominence of the Kearny Mesa Area and can easily accessed off of either the  north or southbound I 163 exits to Genesee  east, or else by using the Mesa College Drive east exit ; or the southbound I 805 west exit all leading Health Center Drive and then to Frost Street.
Sharps also has two on site public pharmacies that are open from daily from to 9am to 6pm - they are closed on weekends and holidays.
I have been to Sharp Memorial a few times over the last two years: I found them to be an excellent organization that cared for me; I felt very comfortable and that they cared for me better than my own siblings have done (After one of my surgeries, I didn't even receive one visitor; I guess that maybe I've never really had any friends?).
During the time I was an inpatient I was brought hot and beverages; the food was very good and they even had a menu. I was even offered warm blankets, when I said that I was cold ( The reason that most hospitals are kept /"cold" is to prevent the spread of germs.).The phlebotomist who drew my blood awesome, as I didn't feel a thing
I was also given a complimentary transit pass, as well as a complementary cab fare - on several occasions - when I had no one to help me get back home; the cab fare was a great help as it was very early in the morning (It was cold and rainy and I would have been left all alone; incidents that took place between Feb. and March of 2017.).
All in all the hospital was extremely clean, the staff seemed to go out of their way to make a personal connection with me - as a patient - and I thought that their 'caring attitudes' were wonderful attributes to their credo that they have attached to themselves as front-line caregivers and leaders  within the San Diego community.
I would like to thank all of those who have treated me for the wonderful jobs that they have done, even though we have had a few disagreements, this is only a small part of my whole life's story.
Since this is a review and whenever I write an evaluation I try to focus on the positive aspects of my experience(s) - I don't review any place that I frequent more than twice that gets below two ‚òÜ's,however anything can change.Three M.D.'s that I saw years before I started using Sharp Memorial will soon get their chance; anyone is free to dispute a negative review..<//Text>< Pics>

<rate>1<//rate><text>I've had nothing but negative experiences at this hospital. From the emergency room to the nurse help line there is very little done right as a whole. It feels very much so like the ER/nursing staff has very little interest in helping their patients.

It took three hours to get seen by a doctor, and she was in a bad state entering - shivering, delirious, hardly able to speak or walk. I've had nothing but negative experiences at this hospital. From the emergency room to the nurse help line there is very little done right as a whole. It feels very much so like the ER/nursing staff has very little interest in helping their patients.

Emergency Room:

I took my girlfriend here at one point and she stayed for over 6 hours just to get two bags of IV fluid following a diagnosis of severe dehydration. It took three hours to get seen by a doctor, and she was in a bad state entering - shivering, delirious, hardly able to speak or walk. At one point later in the stay she waited over an hour and a half with a needle in her arm and an empty IV bag without anyone checking in on her - I had to get a nurse and it became apparent we had been forgotten about following a change in staff. After that we waited another hour just to be told we could leave and that she was fine.

Nurse Help Line:

During our trip to Hawaii recently my girlfriend called in to ask the nurse line for advice regarding nausea. She had been hospitalized a day or so before with a standard case of food poisoning, and she called to ask if feeling nauseous after a meal was normal. She was told by the nurse that she must immediately seek emergency medical care within the next four hours at 2am in the morning, on the other side of the island. I woke up to her crying her eyes out, afraid that she had something horribly wrong with her health. All this because she encountered nausea - a normal symptom of food poisoning - a day after the initial event. She had no symptoms other than an upset stomach.

I really like the Sharp Health System - the urgent care and primary care is excellent, but these experiences at Sharp Memorial have really shaken me. I do not recommend this hospital.< /Review>

< response>

< Pictures>

< userid>
None<//userid>
<name>Hotels.com reviewer</name><Date>1618099200000</Date>< rating>
None</rating>
<text>The Grove Inn is in a residential neighborhood and a good location. We had room 17, second floor, deluxe queen with bay windows. Not a spacious room but sufficient for our needs. I was having surgery at UCSF. Husband stayed 2 nights.  It was very clean, had been remodeled and deluxe bedding which was very comfortable for a good nights sleep.  Nice clean hot shower with new upgraded fixtures. About 10 pm a firetruck and some noisy cars came by and I thought it may be too noisy for me but after that, everything went quiet for the evening.  We felt very safe and saw no homeless on the streets close by. There was no alarm clock in the room therefore using my cell phone for that. Also because of covid, there was no breakfast service and they have a no contact checkin. We did not turn on the tv. There was a nice floor fan with several settings on it which we didn't need. The hosts were very accomodating and very pleasant to talk to on the phone. Even willing to switch our accomodations for a room with 2 beds had we needed it without add. charges. That was very kind of them. We would definitely stay here again. For us, location, safety, cleanliness, upgraded bedding, noise and parking fees were all factors in our decision to stay here. They did not disappoint.<//text><pictures>None< /pictures><response>None<//response><Gmap_id>0x808580a4c08c5a63:0x888af1a45c9d6192<//Gmap_id></record></dataset><record>
< resp>
None<//resp>
<Time>1569185044608< /Time><GmapID>0x808580a4c08c5a63:0x888af1a45c9d6192<//GmapID>< pictures>
[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipM2i7y8qOgF52luvVjyHhp2DDxowxRJ85NNwL71=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPgLSlMpOh2lwgUjv-9CaEYrG5iCUhc3Dudi4Lu=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</pictures>
<username>Christopher Bessette< /username>< Rating>
5< /Rating>
<text>We were in San Francisco for a couple of days for an event at Civic Center Plaza and wanted to find a place within walking distance. I'm so glad we came across The Grove Inn! On our check-in day, we arrived early. The room wasn't available yet, but we were able to store our bags and one of the Inn attendants gave us restaurant and coffee shop recommendations.

We stayed in one of the upstairs rooms facing the street and it was very comfortable! The place has a unique "old house" feel to it, which was very cool. For breakfast, there was coffee, tea, orange juice, fresh bread from a local bakery, as well as other assorted breakfast items (cereal, oatmeal, etc.).

Between the friendliness of the staff, the charm of the building, and the convenience of the location (walking distance to Alamo Square, many restaurants, and Civic Center Plaza), this is undoubtedly a place to which I'll be returning.</text><user_id>105467977864636649645<//user_id></record>

<username>Orbitz reviewer<//username><date>1476489600000< /date>< rate>
None<//rate>
< Text>
This is a very sweet, but still clean and modern inn.  There is a continental breakfast that is more European than American, reminds me of a lot of breakfasts I had in hostels and hotels in Europe.  The breakfast isnt super impressive, but will be enough to fill you up for a day of sight seeing.  When we arrived, someone showed us our room but mentioned that there was a suite available if we would rather have that.  We were traveling with an infant, so we were thrilled to have the suite with an extra room so that we could still have a light/the tv on after the baby went to sleep.  The only negative was that the inn did not have any cribs, which was somewhat surprising.  However, luckily I had called ahead to ask about the crib so we were prepared, and rented a pack-n-play from a baby rental service.  But that is the only negative I would say about the inn, so if you dont need a crib, then I would highly recommend.  I loved the area it was in, and actually booked the inn after asking a friend who recently lived in San Francisco where to stay.  This was not a touristy area at all, but felt more like when you stay in an air bnb and are really in a neighborhood where locals hang out and live.<//Text>

<text>Please DO NOT bring your car here, I feel absolutely violated and taken advantage of. Prepare to read about the nightmare. I needed a head gasket repair on my Suburu Forrester 2009 with 150k miles on it, a common repair for these cars. I trusted Abdul & expected to receive back a safe & reliable vehicle. Instead, I received the car returned with its internal organs beat up, ripped out, assaulted and damaged. My car is currently at a different shop, unable to be used because it's basically an unsafe bomb I refuse to risk my life driving in.

Initially, Abdul said he would cover the cost of any additional work that needed to be done. Upon inspection, the local shop said I would need a WHOLE NEW GASKET SET (they are already leaking) Abdul heard this and went back on his word, he decided he would no longer pay.
Feb 5th- I still have no car & there is so much damage that it may be less expensive to do an entire engine swap than to have all the individual components that ZIPIN OUT has broken fixed individually.

Here's the list of everything wrong:
They didn't replace all the gaskets & some of the gaskets that they did replace are leaking
Hoses not attached
Chipped bell housing
A broken transmission guide pin
Shot tie rod ends- why did they even touch these?
Bolts entirely missing or put in crooked
Wiring harness left dangling & wires for the spark plugs were just sitting on the engine, not put back in place.
Timing belt housing is loose & seems to be damaged but engine needs to be completely removed to inspect. There was ONE SCREW that wasn't even halfway in holding the housing on. (SEE PIC)
The biggest problem now is that the damage they caused when they messed up the pully system... Couldn't start the engine, per Abdul had to open and close 50 times, Pulleys are all chewed up and already damaged belts just from ride home, and his mechanic admits that he "forgot" to close housing once the car started and Abdul says he inspected but clearly not. SEE PIC
There's more that will probably need to be fixed but we don't know yet as we are filing a complaint with the BAR to inspect this car before we get more work done.

Essentially once the car would move they sent it out the door as fast as they could without even bothering to see where the bolts that were sitting on the floor went...

According to our local mechanic, it's likely that there is more work to be done due to their negligence. (Negligence which ZIPIN Out has acknowledged but refuses to fix.)

This is the exact reason I am so pessimistic to take my car into places to be fixed, the stereotype of the young lady being taken advantage of at the car shop holds true once again.

Abdul reviewed to me all the work that was done and gave me a fair price. FAST, FRIENDLY, & FAIR.

UPDATE: I've been going to Zipin Out now for the last few months, and nothing has changed. Excellent service and work. Abdul is sincere and fair. I now send my girlfriend here for her automotive needs. I will continue my business here for a long time to come.</Review>< Pics>

<user>116546227881574377175<//user></record></dataset><record>
<user_id>104140437281161871703</user_id><name>Kristen mariposa</name><date>1582173255656<//date><Rating>5</Rating>< Text>
Updated to share more useful info:
They close at 10pm. Everything automatically shuts off.
$2.25 to start wash. 4 minutes. No tokens needed.
At each station you can use bills, change or credit/debit card. The credit/debit instructions state that the initial swipe automatically charges you for the $2.25 for 4 minutes. Each swipe after that before it times out adds another dollar.
** It also states that a $25.00 hold is placed on the card but when you are finished, the hold is released and  only the final cost is charged. ***
Didnt use the vacuum. But i can vouch for the wash station working. Came at 630pm on a Saturday and was able to wash my car right away. Only 1 stall out of 4 was occupied.
And at 8:30pm on a Wednesday.  3 out of 4 stalls occupied. Not crowded.
Great place to wash your car. Hassle free. The non token options make it so much easier.< /Text>

< Review>
My experiences here have all been positive. The staff is friendly and pretty informative. I never have to wait long in the waiting room or the patient rooms. And when my appointments are in the morning, there's coffee and tea available. Totally a plus in my book!

I've seen 4 different doctors there and they all took the time to talk to me and answer questions. The last doctor I saw, Dr. Tan, is more on the quiet side, so he didn't offer up much information on his own. You have to ask him questions and then he'll give you answers. His assistant was very friendly and helpful, too. She made sure I was getting their emails that provide the doctor's notes, diagnosis, test results, etc. I appreciate having access to this info online because it's hard to remember everything the doctor says, especially when they're treating you for a few things.

I do wish they allowed for walk-ins though because sometimes I'd like to see a doctor right away instead of 3 days later. This is why I didn't give 5 stars. But overall, I'm very happy with Joshua Medical.</Review>

<rate>4</rate><review>Great atmosphere, amazingly friendly and welcoming staff, fair coffee.
There just seems to be a lack of knowledge surrounding the traditional espresso coffee wares(which I realize is slightly a matter of opinion). I was given a dry cappuccino when asking for a macchiato and had to clarify a few times what was even meant by macchiato.
The black coffee was not as light a roast as I would like but that is purely a matter of taste so no fault there. It wasn't bitter or under extracted so I can't fault the personal decision to select this coffee, nor would I want to. The massive diversity in roasting is what makes discovering new shops so exciting.
The blueberry muffin was very good. Not overly sweet, medium density, subtle blueberry flavor which actually paired quite well with the black coffee.
Was able to try the nitro coffee on my way out which was very good for those who like the texture this process brings but want a more nuanced coffee experience.
Overall I'll be returning to this shop mainly because a.they are in a dry area for decent shops and b. The staff is worth the return trip making any other shortcomings easy to overlook.</review>< Pictures>

<gmapID>0x80db7e77ddd25669:0xf8a94cf67991c658</gmapID><Rating>5<//Rating><user_name>Christina Willis</user_name><resp>None</resp><time>1557286441126< /time><pics>None</pics><userid>102764457710133207067<//userid>< Text>
I can see why this coffee shop gets raving reviews. Service is wonderful, and the selection is unique and wide. I went for a cappuccino, my usual menu item at any new to me coffee shop. They use different "milk" types, including almond.

If you order your drink to stay, you get it in a beautiful cup that many people posted pictures of. It is so vibrant and colorful! The drink was very good, and the atmosphere quiet and relaxed. On a Saturday afternoon there were few people there, but I can see how during business hours the coffee shop can get quickly filled up. Seating is plentiful, and decor is somewhat rustic with elements of industrial feel. I generally prefer cozier atmosphere, but to each their own.

I will absolutely come back to try their specialties, now that I established that their cappuccino is worth drinking :)<//Text>

<Time>1485745362666</Time><Rate>5< /Rate>< text>
Delicious tea! Great staff! Tasty pastries!

Love this tea house! It has a very friendly, inviting atmosphere, the teas are wonderful (the chocolate chai latte is one of my favorites!), and the people are so nice!

This is my favorite place to get a hot drink in the cold, and when it gets warm I'll be coming for the iced lattes and blended smoothies!

Also, their tea cups are so adorable!<//text>

<userid>112179861327076124454<//userid>< Review>
My son was a bit scared to go to the dentist for the first time. He had heard "stories" from classmates that had frightened him. A family friend recommended Children's Dental FunZone.

The moment that we walked into the office, we knew that we had made the right choice. The space was clean, colorful, and inviting. From the very beginning, the staff was warm and helpful. I mentioned my child's apprehension and they took extra care to make him feel at ease. They joked around and soon there were smiles for all of us. The dentist was super kind and informative.

To sum up, there were movies and games in the waiting area, a chosen movie during treatment, amazingly sensitive staff, and the whole process was fast. Plus, a prize at the end! We're actually looking forward to our next visit. Highly recommend.</Review>
